  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash happens in
ShuffleVectorInst construction due to invalid operands. Specifically,
BoUpSLP::gather emits a two-operand shufflevector combining Root and the
partially built Vec using a mask. The assertion indicates that the shuffle
operands are not valid \u2014 most commonly because the two vector operands have
different types (e.g., different vector lengths) when creating a two-operand
shuffle.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows \"added a ShuffleVector
op\" early in vectorization of a store chain. The backtrace pinpoints
BoUpSLP::gather creating the shufflevector at SLPVectorizer.cpp:13563. The path
that leads here includes processBuildVector calling
ShuffleInstructionBuilder::gather with a Root value (Vec) from a previous step,
then BoUpSLP::gather tries to combine constants into the Root via a two-operand
shuffle. However, BoUpSLP::gather only special-cases when Root is a
poison-second-operand shuffle of the exact target type; otherwise, it proceeds
without ensuring Root and Vec have the same type.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nBoUpSLP::gather assumes Root and the newly built Vec are of the same
vector type when it calls Builder.CreateShuffleVector(Root, Vec, Mask). There is
no type harmonization (resize/cast) when they differ in number of elements. In
this reproducer, the vectorization builds vectors of size 4, but a previous step
(e.g., a partial vector or sub-vector) can set Root to a different VF (like 2).
The helper ShuffleInstructionBuilder has logic to resize mismatched inputs
(resizeToMatch), but BoUpSLP::gather does not. Therefore, the first
transformation that triggers the crash is the two-operand shuffle creation with
mismatched operand types.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit point in
BoUpSLP::gather to guard and harmonize types before creating the two-operand
shufflevector. If Root exists and Vec is not poison, ensure Root and Vec have
identical vector types. If the element types are the same but the number of
elements differs, resize the smaller operand to the larger using an identity mask
with poison for extra lanes. If element types differ (shouldn't for this path
since ScalarTy drives VecTy), conservatively bail out to using
OriginalRoot.\n\nSuggested replacement for lines 13559-13567:\n\nif (Root) {\n
if (isa<PoisonValue>(Vec)) {\n    Vec = OriginalRoot;\n  } else {\n    // Ensure
both operands have the same vector type before shuffling.\n    Type *Ty1 =
Root->getType();\n    Type *Ty2 = Vec->getType();\n    if (Ty1 != Ty2) {\n
auto *VT1 = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(Ty1);\n      auto *VT2 =
dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(Ty2);\n      if (VT1 && VT2 && VT1->getElementType() ==
VT2->getElementType()) {\n        int VF1 = VT1->getNumElements();\n        int
VF2 = VT2->getNumElements();\n        int VF = std::max(VF1, VF2);\n        int
MinVF = std::min(VF1, VF2);\n        SmallVector<int, 8> IdentityMask(VF,
PoisonMaskElem);\n        std::iota(IdentityMask.begin(), IdentityMask.begin() +
MinVF, 0);\n        Value *&Smaller = (VF1 < VF2) ? Root : Vec;\n        Smaller
= Builder.CreateShuffleVector(Smaller, IdentityMask);\n        // After resizing,
types should match.\n        Ty1 = Root->getType();\n        Ty2 =
Vec->getType();\n      }\n    }\n    // Only emit two-operand shuffle if types
match.\n    if (Ty1 == Ty2) {\n      Vec = Builder.CreateShuffleVector(Root, Vec,
Mask);\n      if (auto *OI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(OriginalRoot);\n          OI
&& OI->hasNUses(0))\n        eraseInstruction(OI);\n    } else {\n      //
Fallback: if unable to harmonize, do not emit invalid shuffle.\n      Vec =
OriginalRoot;\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nThis mirrors the resize policy used in
ShuffleInstructionBuilder::ShuffleIRBuilder::resizeToMatch and prevents
constructing an invalid two-operand shuffle.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is
caused by creating a two-operand shufflevector with mismatched operand types in
BoUpSLP::gather. By introducing a type harmonization step (resizing the smaller
vector to match the larger with an identity mask and poison fill) before emitting
the shuffle, we ensure operands are valid, avoiding the assertion. If
harmonization cannot be achieved (e.g., differing element types), we fall back to
OriginalRoot to preserve correctness and avoid the crash. This fix targets the
first transformation point responsible for the invalid IR.",
